dial","Lateral","Inferior"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal carotid arteries run laterally\u003C/strong\u003E to the pituitary gland within the cavernous sinuses. This is the correct anatomical relationship. The suggestion that they run \u003Cstrong\u003Emedially\u003C/strong\u003E to the gland is incorrect as this would place them within the substance of the gland itself. The arteries do not run \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior\u003C/strong\u003E to the gland as they maintain their lateral course throughout this region. While the internal carotid arteries do have an ascending course, they do not run \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior\u003C/strong\u003E to the pituitary gland at the level of the sella turcica.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this anatomical relationship is crucial for:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EInterpreting radiological imaging of the sellar region\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003ESurgical approaches to pituitary tumours\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EUnderstanding the potential complications of pituitary pathology\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pituitary gland sits in the sella turcica with the internal carotid arteries running laterally through the cavernous sinuses","The anatomical relationship between the pituitary and internal carotid arteries is clinically important for surgical approaches and imaging interpretation"],"references":["Vijaywargiya M, Deopujari R, Athavale SA. Anatomical study of petrous and cavernous parts of internal carotid artery. Anat Cell Biol. 2017 Sep;50(3):163-170. doi: 10.5115/acb.2017.50.3.163. Epub 2017 Sep 20. PMID: 29043093; PMCID: PMC5639169.","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd.","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-24T08:12:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T08:14:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8222"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80948"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships